        output='Based on the provided S-1 Preamble text, here are the comprehensive details regarding **Terafab**, broken down by your requested categories:\n\n### **Glossary Definition**\nIn the Preamble\'s glossary, **“Terafab”** is defined as: *"a chip manufacturing initiative with a long-term goal of producing one terawatt of compute"* (with subsequent sections clarifying this as *"one terawatt of compute hardware each year"*). \n\n### **Terawatt & Compute Capacity**\n*   **Terawatt Definition:** The glossary defines a "terawatt" as one trillion watts. \n*   **Production Capacity:** Terafab’s long-term goal is to achieve an annual production capacity of **one terawatt of compute hardware**. \n*   **Scale:** It is expected to become the **"world’s largest chip manufacturing facility,"** designed to support orders-of-magnitude increases in AI compute deployment and secure the physical constraints of AI growth.\n\n### **Chip Manufacturing**\n*   **Closed-Loop Vertical Integration:** Terafab is designed as a single, closed-loop plant that handles end-to-end manufacturing. This includes the design of lithography masks, the fabrication of logic and memory chips, and the design of advanced packaging. This setup enables rapid testing, iteration, and scaling.\n*   **Dual-Chip Strategy:** The facility will manufacture two distinct types of chips:\n    1.  **Terrestrial Chips:** Optimized for edge and inference workloads, primarily to be used in **Tesla’s Optimus robots and vehicles**.\n    2.  **Space-Optimized Chips:** Hardened and optimized for the space environment to power **SpaceX’s orbital AI compute infrastructure** and satellite constellations.\n*   **Strategic Purpose:** To alleviate future chip shortages, bypass external foundry bottlenecks, and secure the foundational "physical stack" necessary to train and run frontier AI models (like Grok) at high velocity.\n\n### **Timeline**\n*   **March 2026:** SpaceX announced the Terafab initiative and agreed upon a general framework for future development with Tesla.\n*   **Early April 2026:** Intel officially joined the project.\n*   **Future Milestones:** Specific development timelines, milestones, and individual project start dates have **not yet been determined** and are subject to separate, future negotiations and agreements.\n\n### **Capital & Cost**\n*   **Capital Expenditures (CapEx):** Terafab is explicitly listed among the massive infrastructure programs that will require "significant additional capital resources" and substantial future capital expenditures. Exact CapEx figures are currently undetermined.\n*   **Cost Efficiency:** The initiative is expected to "potentially reduce overall compute costs." By applying the same extreme vertical integration philosophy used to manufacture ~80% of the Starship rocket in-house, SpaceX expects Terafab to yield massive speed and cost advantages compared to relying on traditional, third-party external foundries.\n\n### **Organizational Entity & Collaboration**\nTerafab is not a standalone corporate entity, but rather a **massive strategic collaboration** between three primary organizations:\n1.  **SpaceX (including xAI):** The S-1 registrant driving the initiative to secure compute hardware for its orbital AI, Starlink satellite constellations, and frontier model training.\n2.  **Tesla:** A foundational partner providing shared engineering resources, intellectual property, and infrastructure. Tesla will also serve as the primary consumer of the facility\'s terrestrial edge/inference chips.\n3.  **Intel:** Brought into the partnership to contribute its specialized, industry-leading expertise in designing, fabricating, and packaging ultra-high-performance chips at scale to ensure Terafab can meet its massive terawatt-scale goals.',
